20. Performance Considerations

20.1 Avoid full diff by default

Full diff is expensive because it needs to recursively inspect the object.

Only run full diff when:

section hash is different

20.2 Use section-level hashing

Section-level hashing avoids one large opaque hash and gives better diagnostics.

20.3 Limit concurrency

Do not run 1,000 validations at the same time.

Use p-limit.

20.4 Cache fingerprints if possible

If configs change infrequently, store the latest fingerprints.

Example:

dbName + environment + configVersion → section hashes

Then deployment validation can compare stored hashes without recomputing everything.

20.5 Fetch lightweight metadata first

Best case:

Deployment validation fetches only fingerprints first.

Only fetch full config when hashes mismatch.

Recommended long-term design:

Config change event → normalize → hash → store fingerprint
Deployment → compare stored fingerprints
Mismatch → fetch full config → detailed diff


---

21. Recommended Final Flow

The best production flow is:

1. Whenever config changes:
   - Normalize the config
   - Create section hashes
   - Store fingerprints

2. During deployment:
   - Load UAT fingerprints
   - Load PROD fingerprints
   - Compare hashes

3. If all hashes match:
   - Allow deployment

4. If hashes mismatch:
   - Fetch full normalized config only for mismatched databases
   - Run jsondiffpatch only on mismatched sections
   - Write detailed report
   - Block or warn based on section severity


---

22. Summary

The recommended architecture is:

Normalize → Sort unordered arrays → Stable stringify → Section hash → Compare hashes → Diff only mismatches

This approach is fast because most validations are reduced to string comparisons.

It is scalable because it avoids deep comparison and full diff generation unless needed.

It is reliable because normalization and stable stringification guarantee deterministic hash input.

It is developer-friendly because mismatches can still produce detailed human-readable diffs when required.